'''Bryan Lynn Shader''' (born 17 December 1961) is a professor of mathematics at the [[University of Wyoming]]. He received his Ph.D. from [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] in 1990, his advisor was Professor [[R. A. Brualdi|Richard Brualdi]]. Shader is the Editor-in-chief of the ''Electronic Journal of Linear Algebra''. He is also Associate Editor of other two journals, ''[[Linear Algebra and its Applications]]'' (since 2003) and ''Linear & Multilinear Algebra'' (since 2009). He is one of the most active mathematicians working on Combinatorial Matrix Theory.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} He is also noted for his monograph on matrices of sign-solvable linear systems. Besides organizing many workshops he is a Co-PI of Math Teacher Leadership Program, an NSF project (2009–2014). Shader is Special Assistant to the Vice-President of Research of University of Wyoming.
Shader received the 2005 Burton W. Jones Distinguished Teaching Award from the Rocky Mountain Section of the [[Mathematical Association of America]].<ref>[http://sections.maa.org/rockymt/past_awards.html#shader Burton W. Jones Distinguished Teaching Award Recipients] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320231835/http://sections.maa.org/rockymt/past_awards.html#shader |date=March 20, 2012 }}, [[Mathematical Association of America]]. Accessed August 5, 2011</ref>
==Personal life == Bryan Shader has a daughter named Sarah Shader who is currently attending [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] and studying Computer Science and perhaps math.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}
