'''Good–deal bounds''' are price bounds for a [[financial portfolio]] which depends on an individual trader's preferences. Mathematically, if <math>A</math> is a set of portfolios with future outcomes which are "acceptable" to the trader, then define the function <math>\rho: \mathcal{L}^p \to \mathbb{R}</math> by :<math>\rho(X) = \inf\left\{t \in \mathbb{R}: \exists V_T \in A_T: X + t + V_T \in A\right\} = \inf\left\{t \in \mathbb{R}: X + t \in A - A_T\right\}</math> where <math>A_T</math> is the set of final values for [[self-financing trading strategy|self-financing trading strategies]]. Then any price in the range <math>(-\rho(X), \rho(-X))</math> does not provide a good deal for this trader, and this range is called the "no good-deal price bounds."<ref>{{cite journal|title=Coherent Risk Measures, Valuation Bounds, and (<math>\mu,\rho</math>)-Portfolio Optimization|first1=Stefan|last1=Jaschke|first2=Uwe|last2=Kuchler|year=2000}}</ref><ref name="FE">{{cite book|title=Financial Engineering|author=John R. Birge|year=2008|publisher=Elsevier|pages=521–524|isbn=978-0-444-51781-4}}</ref>
If <math>A = \left\{Z \in \mathcal{L}^0: Z \geq 0 \; \mathbb{P}-a.s.\right\}</math> then the good-deal price bounds are the [[no-arbitrage price bounds]], and correspond to the subhedging and [[superhedging price]]s. The no-arbitrage bounds are the greatest extremes that good-deal bounds can take.<ref name="FE" /><ref>{{cite journal|title=Convex risk measures for good deal bounds|first1=Takuji|last1=Arai|first2=Masaaki|last2=Fukasawa|year=2011|url=https://arxiv.org/PS_cache/arxiv/pdf/1108/1108.1273v1.pdf|format=pdf|accessdate=October 14, 2011}}</ref>
If <math>A = \left\{Z \in \mathcal{L}^0: \mathbb{E}[u(Z)] \geq \mathbb{E}[u(0)]\right\}</math> where <math>u</math> is a [[utility function]], then the good-deal price bounds correspond to the [[indifference price]] bounds.<ref name="FE" />
